1
00:00:01,328 --> 00:00:04,000
At what age did you lose your virginity?

2
00:00:04,411 --> 00:00:06,000
Virginity?

3
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:07,996
What is virginity?

4
00:00:07,996 --> 00:00:09,996
Seriously, what is virginity?

5
00:00:11,111 --> 00:00:13,440
At what age did you lose...

6
00:00:13,923 --> 00:00:15,923
…did you have sex for the first time?

7
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:19,682
The first girl I ever had…

8
00:00:19,682 --> 00:00:21,682
was the one who ate the whole pot of fish stew.

9
00:00:23,135 --> 00:00:28,000
Then I had another one, but I lost her after throwing away her gift.

10
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:34,000
And I won’t say more because the one I was about to rape her, I lost her too.

11
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:35,822
And the one I brought to my house,

12
00:00:35,822 --> 00:00:37,532
the one who ate the whole pot of fish stew,

13
00:00:37,532 --> 00:00:39,532
she didn’t want me to touch her or anything.

14
00:00:40,217 --> 00:00:43,372
But she ate it all, the sneaky little mole.

15
00:00:43,493 --> 00:00:49,613
And I saw her breasts because she fell—she had a bruise, a big hematoma.

16
00:00:51,304 --> 00:00:54,000
And her aunt also ate my fish stew at my house.

17
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:55,734
And why didn’t you get married?

18
00:00:55,831 --> 00:00:58,233
I don’t wanna get married. I’m good.

19
00:00:58,233 --> 00:01:00,233
Now that they see me on TV, all the girls stop me in the street.

20
00:01:01,493 --> 00:01:04,000
I’m single, I’m a lone wolf.

21
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:07,469
Because if I marry one, she wins and keeps everything.

22
00:01:07,469 --> 00:01:10,421
And because they watch soap operas, they come running after me.

23
00:01:15,541 --> 00:01:19,073
There are soap operas for the morning, noon, afternoon, and even at night.

24
00:01:23,783 --> 00:01:25,759
And when they get moody, they leave.

25
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:29,734
Do you think men and women are equal?

26
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:33,131
No, men are one thing, women are another.

27
00:01:33,445 --> 00:01:36,044
I admire the way you explain things so clearly.

28
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:40,000
I said it loud and clear, didn’t I?

29
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:41,923
It’s glorious!

30
00:01:44,700 --> 00:01:47,131
Did you hear they say there are gay cops now?

31
00:01:47,469 --> 00:01:51,517
Yeah, I saw it in a magazine. Now you can hook up with them.

32
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:55,000
Are you thinking of coming out of the closet?

33
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:57,000
The closet? What closet?

34
00:01:57,000 --> 00:01:59,000
Closet?

35
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:03,000
I put on my clothes, go out into the street, like always.

36
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:09,000
You know, when people publicly come out as gay, they “come out of the closet.”

37
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:11,000
Come out of the closet? What’s that?

38
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:13,000
Gay?

39
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:14,000
Homosexuals.

40
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,000
Ah, all that stuff.

41
00:02:19,372 --> 00:02:21,000
Well, I don’t know anything about that.

42
00:02:21,894 --> 00:02:24,894
Would you like to be a woman?

43
00:02:27,773 --> 00:02:31,000
Not anymore, I’ll stay as I am.

44
00:02:32,183 --> 00:02:35,000
But if I had been born a woman…

45
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:37,000
Would you have liked it?

46
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:39,000
Yeah, I’d like to be a woman. But I can’t change that.

47
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:41,966
Why would you have wanted to be born a woman?

48
00:02:41,966 --> 00:02:45,000
Because women take everything, they win everything!

49
00:02:56,664 --> 00:03:02,000
The ones who want to be women, even though they’re men…

50
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:04,000
Huh?

51
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:06,000
Pluma, right?

52
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:08,000
Me too.

53
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:10,000
What did you say? Pluma?

54
00:03:12,715 --> 00:03:15,000
I didn’t hear what you said.

55
00:03:15,411 --> 00:03:17,165
Ah, he’s gay, right?

56
00:03:17,648 --> 00:03:19,648
He’s gay, right?

57
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:31,565
Do you know how to iron clothes?

58
00:03:31,831 --> 00:03:32,928
A little.

59
00:03:35,685 --> 00:03:36,840
Pluma.

60
00:03:37,566 --> 00:03:38,432
Pluma?

61
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:41,000
Ironing clothes.

62
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:42,657
Ironing clothes, pants, yeah.

63
00:03:42,657 --> 00:03:43,657
Do you know how to sew?

64
00:03:43,789 --> 00:03:44,551
Yeah, a little.

65
00:03:44,551 --> 00:03:45,996
Pluma.

66
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:49,000
Do you know how to scrub floors?

67
00:03:53,509 --> 00:03:57,000
Damn, now you’re making me doubt myself.

68
00:03:57,000 --> 00:03:59,000
He’s driving me crazy.

69
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:01,000
Just a little, just a little.

70
00:04:03,746 --> 00:04:06,000
That’s what you’d be if you were the big brother.

71
00:04:06,422 --> 00:04:07,799
Risitas, please,

72
00:04:07,799 --> 00:04:11,278
can you tell me how many days you’ve worked

73
00:04:11,278 --> 00:04:12,934
in your entire life?

74
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:16,607
How old are you?

75
00:04:16,607 --> 00:04:21,000
45 years old. I don’t take age like a flower or anything.

76
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:23,000
45 years and still looking good.

77
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:26,000
Can you tell me, please, how many days you’ve worked?

78
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:28,000
I burned the papers.

79
00:04:28,370 --> 00:04:30,491
The ones they gave me when I worked.

80
00:04:30,861 --> 00:04:33,000
But how many days in total, more or less?

81
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:35,000
More or less…

82
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:38,723
In 45 years, have you worked at least one full year?

83
00:04:39,278 --> 00:04:40,862
Seven years.

84
00:04:41,532 --> 00:04:44,000
Seven. Not more than that.

85
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:47,000
Up until today.

86
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:48,515
In 45 years, seven years?

87
00:04:48,515 --> 00:04:49,515
Seven.

88
00:04:49,515 --> 00:04:51,515
Including vacations.

89
00:04:52,347 --> 00:04:57,000
The first thing I asked when I got a job was for vacation days.

90
00:04:57,462 --> 00:05:01,000
And they’d say, "Damn, you just got here, and you’re already asking for vacation!"

91
00:05:01,763 --> 00:05:02,677
Really?

92
00:05:08,960 --> 00:05:12,469
And what’s the hardest job you’ve ever had?

93
00:05:13,277 --> 00:05:15,277
The hardest one, the hardest one… at the beach.

94
00:05:15,393 --> 00:05:16,931
Working at the beach.

95
00:05:17,324 --> 00:05:19,792
From morning till night.

96
00:05:19,792 --> 00:05:20,792
Collecting sand?

97
00:05:20,908 --> 00:05:21,908
Not sand.

98
00:05:21,908 --> 00:05:23,908
I was working like crazy.

99
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:27,000
And what happened to me… I didn’t tell you?

100
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:28,000
At the…

101
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:29,653
At the kitchen.

102
00:05:29,653 --> 00:05:31,445
What the cook made me do.

103
00:05:31,445 --> 00:05:35,000
Clean lettuce, do the laundry, clean the fish…

104
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:38,000
And what happened with the cook that fired me.

105
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:39,000
What happened?

106
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:41,000
I didn’t tell you?

107
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:42,000
I don’t remember.

108
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,000
When I was in Chipiona.

109
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:48,000
I was the new guy, and the cook asks me, "You the new kitchen assistant?"

110
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:49,000
Yeah.

111
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:52,000
"Risitas, right? They told me to call you that."

112
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:54,000
The new guy. How long are you staying?

113
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:58,000
Well, today’s May, Pepe told me till September.

114
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:00,000
And what do you know how to do in the kitchen?

115
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:02,700
Clean fish, make rice…

116
00:06:02,700 --> 00:06:04,723
"Alright, you’ll be the assistant here."

117
00:06:04,723 --> 00:06:07,000
But for your first day, listen up.

118
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:09,000
We’re going to clean everything here.

119
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:10,000
Alright?

120
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:11,353
And then we’ll talk in the morning.

121
00:06:11,515 --> 00:06:14,000
You know that when we open a restaurant,

122
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:16,000
everything has to be spotless.

123
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:17,000
Yes, chef.

124
00:06:18,630 --> 00:06:22,561
We started cleaning at 11 in the morning…

125
00:06:22,561 --> 00:06:25,261
The restaurant had been closed all winter,

126
00:06:25,261 --> 00:06:27,261
we were getting it ready for summer.

127
00:06:27,261 --> 00:06:31,261
By 2 a.m., I had scrubbed, wiped, fried, boiled—everything!

128
00:06:31,261 --> 00:06:33,261
I did EVERYTHING.

129
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:38,000
And then, the chef hands me 20 paelleras.

130
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:41,000
You should’ve seen them—completely covered in mold!

131
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:43,000
"Risitas," he says,

132
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:45,901
"You can’t wash these in the sink."

133
00:06:46,063 --> 00:06:48,422
And by then, my back was already killing me.

134
00:06:48,422 --> 00:06:52,353
From hunching over all day, scrubbing pots and pans.

135
00:06:52,468 --> 00:06:54,000
It was 2 in the morning.

136
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:56,000
And he goes, "Alright, take a break now."

137
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:59,000
"You’ve cleaned the kitchen, tomorrow we open."

138
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:02,283
"Now, take these 20 paella pans"—covered in mold—

139
00:07:02,745 --> 00:07:03,745
"You listening to me?"

140
00:07:03,745 --> 00:07:04,781
"Take a rope,"

141
00:07:04,781 --> 00:07:06,781
"tie them up, and take them to the beach."

142
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:09,000
"Leave them in the water overnight."

143
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:12,000
"The seawater will clean off all the mold."

144
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:14,000
"But make sure you remember where you leave them!"

145
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:15,000
"Wait, what?"

146
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:17,000
"The seawater, with its salt and minerals,

147
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:20,000
will naturally clean the paella pans overnight."

148
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:21,000
"The salt will do the work."

149
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:23,000
"The salt."

150
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:26,000
"The sea, the oranges..."

151
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:27,254
I mean, I get it.

152
00:07:27,462 --> 00:07:30,000
So, at 2 a.m., the chef sends me out to the beach.

153
00:07:30,209 --> 00:07:33,000
"They need to understand you because you’re getting paid for this."

154
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:35,000
Oh, right. Sorry.

155
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:37,000
The magical seawater treatment.

156
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:39,000
I mean, the people down there, they understand, right?

157
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:41,000
The audience.

158
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:43,000
The salt cleans them, that’s what I meant.

159
00:07:43,416 --> 00:07:46,676
Not like Holy Week, no—I'm talking about oranges.

160
00:07:48,786 --> 00:07:51,370
"Risitas, take the 20 paella pans,"

161
00:07:51,370 --> 00:07:54,000
"Tie them up and leave them in the sea."

162
00:07:54,393 --> 00:07:57,000
"But make sure you remember where you put them,"

163
00:07:57,000 --> 00:08:00,000
"because tomorrow morning you’ll have to go get them."

164
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:03,000
So at 2 a.m., I go down to the beach, and the tide is low.

165
00:08:03,740 --> 00:08:07,393
I do exactly as he said—I tie them up, leave them in the water.

166
00:08:07,532 --> 00:08:09,000
I stick a wooden stake in the sand as a marker.

167
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:12,000
Then I go back to the restaurant—it’s now 2:30 a.m.

168
00:08:12,208 --> 00:08:14,693
"Risitas, did you do it?"

169
00:08:14,901 --> 00:08:16,462
"Yes, chef."

170
00:08:16,462 --> 00:08:19,000
"Alright, remember, I’ll wake you up at 8 a.m."

171
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:21,000
"Go get the paella pans then."

172
00:08:21,994 --> 00:08:23,532
So I go to bed.

173
00:08:23,532 --> 00:08:26,000
The restaurant is ready to open, the rice is prepped.

174
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:28,000
At 2 p.m., the chef wakes me up.

175
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:30,000
"Risitas!"

176
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:32,000
"What?"

177
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:34,000
"Go get the paella pans!"

178
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:36,000
"Let’s go, it’s already 2 p.m.!"

179
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:38,000
I throw on my swimsuit,

180
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:40,000
grab my flip-flops, half-dressed—no time to waste.

181
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:42,000
I get to the beach…

182
00:08:44,277 --> 00:08:46,878
And the tide had COME BACK IN!!!

183
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:49,238
JESÚS.

184
00:08:56,000 --> 00:08:58,000
JESÚS.

185
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:00,878
I start digging around in the water, and…

186
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:05,515
I only found ONE paella pan!

187
00:09:07,693 --> 00:09:09,000
Just one!

188
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:11,509
The only reason I found it was because it got stuck

189
00:09:11,509 --> 00:09:14,000
between the rocks by the Chipiona lighthouse.

190
00:09:14,670 --> 00:09:16,659
And when I walk back into the restaurant,

191
00:09:16,844 --> 00:09:18,752
I go up to the chef… holding one single paella pan.

192
00:09:18,965 --> 00:09:20,647
And he just looks at me and says—

193
00:09:20,647 --> 00:09:22,647
"Where are the rest of them?"

194
00:09:25,087 --> 00:09:26,301
Bend down.

195
00:09:26,439 --> 00:09:28,439
Bend down and look where the water reached!

196
00:09:31,156 --> 00:09:33,156
The water had reached all the way to the restaurant!

197
00:09:40,439 --> 00:09:41,561
JESÚS.

198
00:09:41,561 --> 00:09:43,561
"What do we do now?!"

199
00:09:43,561 --> 00:09:45,561
We had two huge sacks of rice ready for the grand opening!

200
00:09:48,254 --> 00:09:50,254
"CALL SEVILLE! CALL SEVILLE!"

201
00:09:50,254 --> 00:09:52,300
"Tell them to bring more paella pans!!!"

202
00:10:01,538 --> 00:10:03,538
JESÚS.

203
00:10:03,538 --> 00:10:05,538
And there I was, standing there…

204
00:10:05,538 --> 00:10:07,538
…in my swim trunks…

205
00:10:07,538 --> 00:10:09,538
…holding one tiny paella pan.

206
00:10:09,538 --> 00:10:11,538
And the chef just stared at me.

207
00:10:11,769 --> 00:10:13,769
"Don’t just stand there! Go to Seville!"

208
00:10:13,769 --> 00:10:15,769
And on the last day, when the Virgin of Regla procession passed by,

209
00:10:15,769 --> 00:10:17,769
we were all in tears.

210
00:10:17,607 --> 00:10:19,607
He paid me for that one little paella pan.

211
00:10:21,700 --> 00:10:23,700
He gave me 500 pesetas for it.

212
00:10:25,237 --> 00:10:26,613
And I never went back.

213
00:10:26,613 --> 00:10:28,613
I left.

214
00:10:28,613 --> 00:10:30,613
I took off walking toward Amarillo.

215
00:10:31,733 --> 00:10:33,456
JESÚS.

216
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:37,700
He sent me…

217
00:10:37,700 --> 00:10:38,200
He sent me—

218
00:10:41,884 --> 00:10:43,630
He sent me at night!

219
00:10:43,630 --> 00:10:45,630
The tide was low when I left them there… but by morning, it had come back in!

220
00:10:48,855 --> 00:10:50,855
Who knows where those paella pans ended up!

221
00:10:50,925 --> 00:10:52,925
They probably drifted all the way to—

222
00:10:53,041 --> 00:10:54,763
—the oil tanker!

223
00:10:55,930 --> 00:10:57,006
The Prestige!

224
00:10:57,006 --> 00:10:58,130
Yeah, the Prestige!

225
00:11:04,300 --> 00:11:07,086
And I never worked in a kitchen again.

226
00:11:07,086 --> 00:11:09,086
I HATE KITCHENS!

227
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:20,231
But hey, at least he gave me a little money from the tip jar.

228
00:11:23,214 --> 00:11:25,214
How much was in the tip jar?

229
00:11:25,307 --> 00:11:27,492
The money he threw at me,

230
00:11:27,492 --> 00:11:29,492
the money I actually earned…

231
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:32,000
…he made me pay for the 20 paella pans!

232
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:34,000
At 500 pesetas each!

233
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:36,000
I mean, you should’ve seen how I left for Seville!

234
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:38,000
I was already bored without the beach.

235
00:11:43,445 --> 00:11:45,445
Oh man, we laughed so much!

236
00:11:50,694 --> 00:11:52,694
Jesús, it’s fine.

237
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:00,000
I don’t want any more rice, Jesús!

238
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:02,000
Not even Chinese rice!
